#week-title("Two", "Antimony as the Chaos of the Sages")

=== Core Teaching

Antimony's unique position in the tradition is that of a seed-bearer for the
metallic kingdom: it is called the *Chaos of the Sages* because it contains
within itself, in accessible and separable form, the three principles that
underlie all metallic development — the Sulphur (its native combustible
sulfide fraction), the Mercury (its volatile spirit, accessible through the
Via Humida), and the Salt (its fixed metallic body, the Regulus).

*The Star Regulus.* When stibnite is reduced by fusion with iron (iron nails
or iron shavings served as the reducing agent in the classical preparations),
the metallic antimony separates from its sulfide and settles to the bottom of
the crucible as a dense, brilliant metal called the Regulus of Antimony. When
this Regulus is remelted and allowed to cool slowly, it often displays a
characteristic stellated (star-shaped) pattern on its upper surface — caused
by the crystallisation of antimony in its cubic system. This is the Star Regulus,
and its appearance was regarded in the tradition as a reliable sign of correct
preparation.

The Star Regulus bears a specific relationship to gold: when fused together,
the Regulus takes up the base metals present (copper, lead, iron) and, on
repeated refusion and separation, releases them — leaving the gold purified.
This is the Wolf devouring the metallic king and returning him perfected.

*Van Suchten on the Three Essentials.* Van Suchten's *Of Antimony Vulgar*
provides one of the most explicit classical descriptions of separating the
three alchemical principles from stibnite:
- The *Sulphur* is found in the native sulphide itself — the combustible,
  roasted fraction.
- The *Mercury* is the Regulus in its active, dissolving aspect — capable of
  carrying and transmitting metallic virtue.
- The *Salt* is the fixed residue after calcination — the antimony oxide
  fraction (with all safety requirements fully in force for its production).

=== Topics This Week

- Antimony as seed-bearer: the Chaos of the Sages
- The Star Regulus: what it is, how it forms, what it indicates
- Van Suchten's Three Essentials from stibnite
- Antimony's purifying relationship to gold: the Wolf and the king

#inner-work[
  *DES-2: The Archetypal at Depth*

  In the analytical depth approach, the figures encountered in the descent are
  understood as archetypal rather than personal: they represent universal
  patterns operating through the individual psyche, not merely personal
  memories or fears.

  In this week's waking dream, descend and attend to whether the figures or
  structures you encounter have taken on a more universal, less personal quality
  than in earlier descents. Are they recognisable as archetypes — the Great
  Mother, the Shadow, the Wise Elder, the Trickster? Record without interpreting
  forcibly; simply describe what you observe.
]

